      <h3>Motor Direction</h3>
      <div class="note">
        <strong>Forward rotation</strong> is clockwise at the workpiece (counterclockwise when viewed from the handpiece end facing you). Forward is the most commonly used setting; right-handed users get the most control in forward. <strong>Reverse rotation</strong> is counterclockwise at the workpiece. Left-handed users have better control in reverse. Alternating direction extends the life of abrasive points, buffs, brushes, and sanding bands.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li>Some handpieces (chisel H.15, hammer H.28, angle grinder) work <strong>only in forward</strong>. Using them in reverse can damage the handpiece, shaft, or motor.</li>
        <li>Use forward only for fluted burs, drills, and cutters &mdash; they cut efficiently only in this direction.</li>
        <li>Many mandrels have right-hand threaded arbor screws that will unscrew in reverse.</li>
        <li>Reverse is useful for &ldquo;backing out&rdquo; stuck drill bits and for symmetrical grinding and carving techniques.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <div class="danger">
