      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>General Guidelines</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Read all safety instructions before operating.</li>
        <li>The motor may be operated vertically or horizontally but should not be enclosed or confined so as to restrict air circulation.</li>
        <li>Hold the handpiece securely before selecting the rotation direction and turning the motor on.</li>
        <li>Begin with a light touch, start slowly, and gradually increase speed.</li>
        <li>Let the speed of the tool do the work &mdash; avoid excessive pressure.</li>
        <li>Generally, slower speeds are used for rougher, heavier work or when greater control is required for delicate work. Higher speeds are used for buffing, cutting, and polishing.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        The motor may develop a high operating temperature (up to 100&deg;F above ambient) after prolonged use and will be too hot to hold. This is normal and will not harm the motor, which is designed to operate at this temperature for extended periods.
      </div>

      <h3>Proper Shaft Handling</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_00.png" alt="Diagram showing correct minimum 4-inch radius bend for flexible shaft" />
        <figcaption>Maintain a minimum 4&Prime; radius bend to extend shaft life</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_01.png" alt="Diagram showing incorrect sharp bend that damages the shaft" />
        <figcaption>Do not bend shaft at a tight angle</figcaption>
      </div>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Do not bend the shaft and sheath at a tight angle.</strong> Shafts and sheaths last longer when used without sharp bends. If used at angles or loops, wear will occur at the points of greatest friction. Maintain a minimum 4&Prime; radius at all times.
      </div>

      <h3>Turning Off the Motor</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove foot from foot pedal speed control (or turn dial control to &ldquo;off&rdquo;).</li>
        <li>Wait for the motor to stop rotating completely.</li>
        <li>Set the rocker switch to &ldquo;off&rdquo; (center) position.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Always make sure your power tool is unplugged when performing maintenance!</strong>
      </div>

      <h3>Routine Motor Cleaning</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_02.png" alt="Motor housing showing air circulation slots" />
        <figcaption>Motor housing air inlet and outlet slots</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Motors need air circulation through the housing to remove waste heat. Sawdust and conductive debris (metal filings, gold dust) can enter through the air slots and cause electrical shorts.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cleaning interval:</strong> Every 40 hours of use in high-dust environments.</li>
        <li>Remove motor brushes and blow compressed or canned air through the motor.</li>
        <li>Clean the motor brushes and check for wear.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note">
        The motor has permanently lubricated ball bearings and does not require additional lubrication.
      </div>

      <h3>Flexible Shaft Lubrication</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_04.png" alt="Loosening the set screw on the motor connector" />
          <figcaption>Step 2: Loosen set screw</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_05.png" alt="Sliding outer sheath out of motor connector" />
          <figcaption>Step 3: Slide sheath out</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_06.png" alt="Applying grease to the inner shaft" />
          <figcaption>Step 4: Apply light coating of grease</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>The flexible inner shaft should be cleaned, wiped, and relubricated with grease every <strong>40 hours</strong> of use. Every <strong>200 hours</strong>, thoroughly clean with solvent before relubricating. Use Foredom flex shaft grease (p/n MS10006) or high-quality white lubricating grease.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove handpiece.</li>
        <li>Loosen the set screw on the motor connector.</li>
        <li>Slide outer sheath out of motor connector and wipe inner shaft clean.</li>
        <li>Apply a very light coating of grease starting at the top and working downward to about 5&Prime; from the handpiece end. Use your fingertip or a small brush. Apply less near the handpiece end to prevent seepage.</li>
        <li>Replace and adjust sheath so the key tip extends 3/4&Prime; (19 mm) from the sheath. Retighten set screw.</li>
        <li>Clean outside of sheath by wiping with a cloth.</li>
        <li>Hang motor over an empty trash can and run for about 15 minutes before attaching the handpiece. This allows the grease to warm, spread, and drain off.</li>
        <li>Wipe off excess grease at the tip end of the sheath, then re-attach handpiece.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_07.png" alt="Readjusting shaft to extend 3/4 inch beyond sheath" />
        <figcaption>Readjust shaft to 3/4&Prime; extension after reassembly</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p06_08.png" alt="Shaft tip types: key tip, square drive, and slip joint" />
        <figcaption>Shaft tip types</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Replacing Worn Shafts and Sheaths</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p07_00.jpg" alt="Motor connector removal with wrench" />
        <figcaption>Remove motor connector with 1&Prime; wrench (left-hand thread &mdash; turn clockwise to remove)</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p07_01.jpg" alt="Motor shaft, coupling, and connector detail" />
        <figcaption>Motor shaft, coupling, and connector</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Under normal conditions, a flex shaft machine may require several replacement shafts and sheaths during its lifetime. Shafts and sheaths last longer when not used at sharp angles.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Expose the inner shaft (remove handpiece, loosen set screw, slide sheath out).</li>
        <li>Remove the motor connector with a 1&Prime; open-end or adjustable wrench. <strong>The motor connector has a left-hand thread &mdash; turn clockwise to remove.</strong></li>
        <li>Remove old shaft. Loosen set screw on new shaft&rsquo;s motor coupling and slide coupling onto motor shaft.</li>
        <li>Tighten set screw securely onto the flat of the motor shaft.</li>
        <li>Grease the new shaft before putting on the sheath.</li>
        <li>Slide motor connector back up over the shaft and tighten to the left (counterclockwise).</li>
        <li>Slide sheath over flexible shaft with the plain fitting toward the motor and into the motor connector. (The grooved end fits the handpiece.)</li>
        <li>Adjust shaft extension to 3/4&Prime; (19 mm) and tighten sheath set screw.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Replacing Motor Brushes</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-sr/p07_02.jpg" alt="Motor brushes showing new brush vs. worn brush needing replacement" />
        <figcaption>New motor brush (left) vs. brush that needs replacement (right)</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Motor brushes should be checked periodically. New brushes are approximately 3/4&Prime; (19 mm) long. Replace when worn to 1/4&Prime; (6 mm).</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Disconnect the motor power cord.</li>
        <li>Unscrew the brush caps (one on each side of the motor).</li>
        <li>Remove worn motor brushes.</li>
        <li>Replace with new motor brushes and screw caps back on.</li>
        <li>Always replace both motor brushes even if one appears less worn.</li>
      </ol>

