      <h3>Storage</h3>
      <p>Store your Foredom power tool in a dry, clean, dust-free area, out of reach of children.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Possible Cause</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Motor does not start</td>
            <td>Speed control not connected or not turned on; fwd/off/rev switch in &ldquo;off&rdquo; position</td>
            <td>Check all connections. Ensure motor is plugged into speed control (never directly into wall outlet). Set switch to forward or reverse.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Motor runs but accessory does not turn smoothly</td>
            <td>Handpiece not properly engaged on key tip; shaft not adjusted correctly</td>
            <td>Remove and re-attach handpiece following the alignment procedure. Check that shaft extends 3/4&Prime; beyond sheath.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Excessive vibration or noise</td>
            <td>Shaft bent at too tight an angle; worn shaft or sheath; worn motor brushes</td>
            <td>Maintain minimum 4&Prime; radius. Replace worn shaft/sheath. Check and replace motor brushes if worn to 1/4&Prime;.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Motor overheats (too hot to touch)</td>
            <td>Normal after prolonged use; restricted air circulation; excessive load</td>
            <td>Motor is designed to run hot (up to 100&deg;F above ambient). Ensure motor is not enclosed. Reduce pressure on accessory.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Fuse blows on dial speed control</td>
            <td>Motor overloaded</td>
            <td>Replace fuse (located below detachable power cord receptacle). Reduce load.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Shaft or sheath wears prematurely</td>
            <td>Sharp bends in shaft; insufficient lubrication; dirt buildup</td>
            <td>Maintain 4&Prime; minimum radius. Clean and relubricate shaft every 40 hours. Clean thoroughly with solvent every 200 hours.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Grease seeping from handpiece end</td>
            <td>Too much grease applied to shaft</td>
            <td>Apply less grease near the handpiece end. Run motor over trash can for 15 minutes to drain excess after greasing.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

